snippet.textDisplay:
When the US did not adopt the successful W.H.O. coronavirus test on Feb 17th, this failure would blind our response. Earlier in Jan. the virus had already spread via air travel to the US. That's when testing would be at its maximum response value. The decision to develop "our" own test would leave us blind for another 2 months (at least) and the failure of "our" test has left us still largely blind today - March 17. We still don't know where the virus is and where it is spreading. We've always had the capacity to immediately adopt the W.H.O. protocol (testing procedure).The consequences of not using the most immediately available (and successful) method to track the virus in the US has had cascading effects. We're fighting blind. We only have a very partial understanding of who sick in the US. Our leaders simply failed to use the quickest defense when speed provided the first and most important defense.
It's little different than being faced with a school shooting and refusing to respond immediately with a borrowed gun, and instead running home hoping to find your own gun. You sacrifice the obvious and important variable - time.

Basically everyone's well being depends on global trade and globally we're hurting, therefore buy gold and pray.
